time required: 25 minutes
---

Pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, add @salt{0.25%tsp}. Stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, trim the @pak choi{1} then thinly slice widthways. Halve the @green pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks and all). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the @salted peanuts{25%g}.

Heat a splash of oil in a large #frying pan{} over a medium high heat. When hot, add the green pepper and cook until starting to soften and brown, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the @king prawns{150%g} and pak choi and cook for a further ~{3-5%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Add the garlic and @Thai green curry paste{45%g} and stir well to combine. Cook stirring frequently until everything is coated well in the paste, ~{1%minute}.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}. Stir in half of the chopped coriander and set aside.

Start by sharing the coriander rice between your plates. Top with the green Thai prawn mix. Sprinkle on the chopped peanuts and remaining coriander. Enjoy!

> Nourishing, flavour-packed, and bursting with fresh green veggies, this nourishing 25-minute curry is a guaranteed crowd-pleaser. Our special Thai curry paste gives the dish a brilliant kick of heat, whilst the peanut garnish adds a beautiful layer of texture. Served on a bed of steamed rice, and topped with chopped coriander this is fast food at its best.